# String Interpolation ($)

**Category**: Operators → String  
**Operator**: `$` in strings  
**Purpose**: Embed expressions

---

See [String Interpolation](interpolation.md) for complete documentation.

---

## Quick Reference

```aria
// Simple variable
name: string = "Alice";
msg: string = "Hello, $name!";

// Expression
x: i32 = 10;
text: string = "Value: ${x + 5}";

// Method calls
info: string = "Status: ${user.status()}";
```

---

**Remember**: `$variable` or `${expression}` in strings!

```aria
// Demonstration of blueprint-style pointer syntax
// Visual directionality encodes semantic meaning - like door swings on blueprints!
//
// POINTER TYPE: int32->  (arrow points TO the type being pointed to)
// ADDRESS-OF:   @var     (at address of variable)  
// DEREFERENCE:  <-ptr    (arrow pulls value FROM pointer)
// NULL COALESCE: ptr ?? default (dereference or use default if null)

func:main = int32() {
    print("=== Blueprint-Style Pointer Syntax Demo ===\n");

    // 1. Create value and get its address
    int32:original = 123i32;
    int32->:pointer = @original;   // @ = "at address of original"

    print("1. Got address with @ operator\n");

    // 2. Dereference to get value back  
    int32:retrieved = <-pointer;   // <- = "pull value FROM pointer"

    print("2. Dereferenced with <- operator\n");

    // 3. Null coalescing - pointer is valid, should dereference
    int32:coalesced = pointer ?? 999i32;

    print("3. Null coalesce returned dereferenced value\n");

    // All three values should be 123
    print("=== All operators working! ===\n");

    pass(coalesced);  // Exit with 123
};

func:failsafe = NIL(int32:err_code) {
    // Error handling
};

```

Use `pass()` — Aria does NOT have a `return` keyword.

```aria
func:add = int32(int32:a, int32:b) {
    pass(a + b);   // CORRECT: use pass()
    // return a + b;   ← WRONG: Aria has no return keyword
};

func:void_func = NIL() {
    // do some work...
    pass(NIL);   // CORRECT: NIL is Aria's void
    // return;  ← WRONG
};
```

`pass(value)` signals successful completion and returns the value.
`fail(code)` signals an error with an integer error code.

Every non-NIL function path must end with `pass(value)`.

Pointers in Aria use the `->` suffix after the type name:

```aria
// Pointer to int32
int32->:ptr;

// Pointer to a struct
Node->:next;

// Wild pointer (mutable)
wild int32->:buf;
```

There is NO `*` pointer syntax in Aria. Use `->` for all pointers.
Null pointers are not supported — Aria uses Result<T> for optional values.

